Very nice video clearing all the deliberate confusion created by TVS. 

I recently bought an ola s1x 4kwh variant at 1.05 lakhs on an offer. Just done 300km so far in 20 days. I did 2 long round trips of 63 and 65km each at speeds of 35 to 42 but mostly 35kmph on cruise  and used up 34% and 35% of charge respectively. That's 1.85 km per 1% of charge. So that's 65km for 35% charge and should easily amount to 150km in 90% leaving you 10% charge spare to cover for anxieties. all this with normal mode and not eco. So ola's claim of 162km on eco mode is not fake at all, its achievable. Of course, my only skill was to never touch the brakes, judge distance beforehand and adjust throttle or use manual regen braking. Im very happy with the results. My weight is 73 and can say 75kg with my clothes and half helmet. Centre stand and mats could add another kg to the kerb weight in total.

text: I think that scooter he reviewed was from generation 1 or 2, I guess. Newer models having ability to tighten rear brake as per requirement. Actually there is difference between hardness of front brake pads and rear brake shoes, so deterioration occurs easily in rear brake shoes easily than brake pads. Hence company provided option for tightening of rear brake in later versions. It's a combo brakes system and if rider applies only rear brake both brakes got engaged but proportion of rear brake is on higher side and so the wear is. In previous versions there was throttle cable. He is right that TVS assures more safety but as per them this is family scooter and if there is kid on the front area  there are chances of scooter getting accidentally accelerated by kid. The reason why there is throttle + brake option in both iqube and new Jupiter 110 too.
